a 4 margo 1682
London mr. William Pindan
In answers to yd of 9 past do here inclosed sond you a leter to m. Timas Seamon
open which you may peruse & deliver him, & in case he will nott pay you shall send you
a procuratin to make him pay heowes mee about ƒ250- butt he hath a cloth insol
here, & that I should take to mee, in case he will pay you the rest I you examn
yd acctt of goods sold, you will finde him charged 1680, 3 & 16 august pray endeavoir
to moeure this, & att this side I hope to gett the rest to cleare yd ballance
London m Domes Seaman

I have sent you the 21 past yd acctt. curt. dixceted to m. roger sones by which is due to mee
ƒ 161.4 ½ besides a cloth unsold, & if you pay this ballance, then I should keep the cloth, se
continew freindes, I have then also desidered you to pay the ballance to m. Ry. senes which if you
have don will be to content, butt if nott, shall give mee cause to gett itt from you, by what
meanes so ever, & send my procuraton to m. vWill Pindar to that piipose, for you know you
have had the serges hy ord. of d. Richd. Southell of Lille, & they werefor acctt. of sand m.
Pondar, now if you have not payd yett, pray pay itt without any dllay to m. soes or
m. Pindar, the complyance of which I expect, withert faile
64 meert 1682 anwerp
London r. Rogen Sone
In antwer to yd of 30 Jau. I must assure you, that what I wrott to you, was not without
reason, & that you beleave to have aight to make mee fay by lanw, is yd mistake, for I doubt
you should not finde itt to yd minde, I am forry you took soomich paines to make so long a
letter, for I am not Ignorant of what I did, neither would you have mee buy any thingh without
I had seen itt, & you knew the goods were damaged, principally , so I ordered them, to be send
in, & had they been good, & well for their prijse, I might have kept them, butt they not being
vere well vendable would not keep them for my acctt. so much I should have told you had
you or u caman been here, where I was accovered, & in a londihin to see goods, yett to
make an end & not to shouble you any longer, will you sell y att 37 st an l, I'll pay
y presentley, if not I'll sell them for ydt acctt or deliver them to m. Breusegem upon yd
anwer for I can hott trouble my head longer wish itt, though I had no thought, butt
that I was th to pay y to m. Leaman, whom I have ordered to pay you ƒ 165:4 - which
If he hath don shall be upon acctt. of red dosins, if not, you see here the prepositton which
is vere faire, for I dolove to remaine freinds beeng
Londen mr. Paris slaughten
In answer to yd of 6 & 10 past as to the concernes of m. Peeters I observe that mr. maynard
hath told you the needfull, the ballance of their acctt. is now £396„6„8, haveing payd by
orderen of m maynaard the heares of the inden Bouwens for charges don by them, as by
acctt. & acque, is to be aseen, besides ap of linnes for wrapper & charges on the pack
of cloathes returned. I have remitted you £120-, & there will be about £100 more coming
of which m. Sames rsprest will dcouise you att large, & hope finde out away to sett an end
on that bustijnes the is gon forward yeasterday, & so referre my silf to him se
Londen mr. Michiel Peeters
sedert dat m. maynard hier heeft geweest hebbe geremitt. aen mr. slanghter £ 120- st
daer en tusten m. Jac erspreet, is van hier naer costi vertrocken, & heeft mij belooft aen ul alle
mogelijcke aftsretentie te doen om de saken ten eijnde te brengen, volgens dan advijs sal becomen
sal de rest remitt. Ick tien sij blijven seer op hunne opine, & sonden mij wel blameeren
dat seg te veel aenhoude voor ul &

Londen m Denry Maynard
mj last to you was on the 28 past to which referre you prtncipally about the brownish cullours
amonghst which you might assort 2 a 3 drap cullours as N. 939 & 961 last sent of the keys
on the bike butt pray avoid all sort of broad mipture, for our people will have hardely anymishre
inclosed my answer to mr slaughter, m. sames espaeet is gon for london to you may prefare the
2 giinigs & hee promised to make ande end in the bustijnes of Peeters, I wish he may
inclosed a bill on m. John Loyd, for which ray pioeure acceptance & returne mee, inclosed also a
note of Jhom: whitbye to which I payd according to yd. ad. of 5 feb ƒ 100- & made yd acct dibtir
he is gon over with his sonn rcleased ly way of holland, & I desived him to provide for mee a banill
of flying ale, ot beare & ailes to be sent mee in a duble cash to be bottled here he promised
he would provide the best, that ever came out of Englant, I could wish itt wash not to strong, butt such
as you sended mee. 2 yeare ago, observe that the barnell must not be to full that itt should not
breake att sea: as then most part of the bottled did, pray assit him in itt, & pay him the
valeu for my acctt, & lett the bargell be good & strong, & the second also, & a matt about then
bannell, that I might not be cheated under whyce
